When this rule is mentioned use this documentation:

# Query Builder

The query builder is a feature that allows you to build queries in a declarative way. It is used to define the structure 
of the data that will be returned by an operation. The query builder is used in conjunction with the `@QueryBuilder` 
annotation to define the structure of the data that will be returned by an operation.

## Components

The query builder is composed of the following components:

- **Object type**: The type of the object that will be returned by the operation. This is defined by the `@ObjectType` 
  annotation.

- **Projected fields**: The fields that will be returned by the operation. This is defined by the `@FieldSelector` 
  annotation.

- **Filters**: The filters that will be applied to the data. This is defined by the `@ResultSetFilter` annotation.

- **Limit and offset**: The number of records to return and the offset from which to start returning records. This is 
  defined by the `@Limit` and `@Offset` annotations.

- **Order by**: The fields by which to order the results. This is defined by the `@OrderBy` annotation.

## Example

The following example shows how to define a query builder for an operation that returns a list of users:

```
@OperationElement()
var getUsers : Operation<GetUsersInputType, GetUsersOutputType, ResultFailure<GenericErrorResult, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({
            method: 'GET',
            path: "/users"
        })
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response.body as GetUsersOutputType)
        else
          failure(response.body as GenericErrorResult)
    }
}

type GetUsersInputType = {
    @QueryBuilder()
    query: Query
}

type Query = {
    @ObjectType()
    objectType: String,
    @FieldSelector()
    fields: Array<String>,
    @ResultSetFilter()
    filters: Array<Filter>,
    @Limit()
    limit: Int,
    @Offset()
    offset: Int,
    @OrderBy()
    orderBy: Array<OrderBy>
}

type Filter = {
    field: String,
    operator: String,
    value: String
}

type OrderBy = {
    field: String,
    direction: String
}

type GetUsersOutputType = {
    users: Array<User>
}

type User = {
    id: String,
    name: String,
    email: String
}
```

Query builder is a UX created for building queries in a way that abstracts users from the query language/query APIs 
and provides a consistent experience. A query builder defines building blocks that are used to expose the different 
query models that are supported on each connector. These building blocks can be combined, ignored, or extended to 
adapt to the capabilities of the target query language/API. Query builder might be used either for operations or triggers.

The parts of the query builder are:
- object type
- projected fields
- filters
- limit and offset
- order by

To create an operation with query builder, the input type has to have the annotation `@QueryBuilder`, define the output type of the 
operation depending on object type and projected fields and write functions to transform the input type to the query 
language of the SaaS. In case of a trigger, the input type is defined in the operation it relies and the
`@QueryBuilder` annotation must not be present. It's only for operations. 

```
@OperationElement()
var queryBuilder : Operation<QueryBuilderInputType, QueryResult<DynamicOutputType>, ResultFailure<GenericErrorResult, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "queryBuilder",
    displayName: "Query",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({
            method: 'GET',
            path: "/query?q=" ++ queryToSoql(parameter)
        })
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response.body as QueryResult<DynamicOutputType>)
        else
          failure(response.body as GenericErrorResult)
    }
}
```
## Object Type

Defines the type of object that will be queried and will contain the name of the type to be queried. The value of the 
selected object type will be used to determine the output type for the query builder operation/trigger. To provide the required 
query builder UX, a value provider must be attached to this field so the user can get the list of available types.

```
type QueryBuilderInputType = @QueryBuilder() {
    objectType: @ValuesFrom(value = { name: "valueProviderName" }) String
}
```
Reminder: For trigger types, the @QueryBuilder() annotation must not be present. 

## Projected fields

The capability of selecting which fields must be included in the result set varies depending on the connected application. 
In some cases, no filtering is possible and all fields will always be returned. In other cases, both all fields (ie: select *) 
or a custom selection of fields will be possible. The projected fields property will be used, along with the value of the 
selected object type, to determine the output type for the query builder operation/trigger.

The functionality for selecting all/custom field selection can be modeled using a union type with a discriminator field.
To provide the requested UX for custom field selection, the UI needs to have access to the fields and their types for
the selected object. 

The retrieval of this data is done by using a Value Provider that depends on the selected object type. 
A FieldSelector and Discriminator annotations will be needed to mark the query model property where this must be applied.

```
type QueryBuilderInputType = @QueryBuilder() {
    projectedFields: @FieldSelector()
                     @Discriminator(value = {key: "kind"})
                        (AllFieldsSelection | CustomFieldsSelection<@ValuesFrom(value = { name: "queryBuilderFieldsValueProvider", arguments: {objectType: "/objectType"}}) String>)
}
```
Reminder: For trigger types, the @QueryBuilder() annotation must not be present.

## Filters

A condition indicates the name of the field where the condition applies, an operator to apply to the field's value, and 
optionally another value to use in conjunction with the field's value and operator. This value is optional as there are 
unary operators (ex: isNull) that apply to the field's value only.

When defining a filter on a query, there are different variations to consider: No condition, conditions using ANDs, 
conditions using ORs, custom condition. Whether each alternative is available on a given query builder will depend 
on the target SaaS. These different scenarios can be modeled using a union type with a discriminator to indicate the type of 
condition. A ResultSetFilter annotation will be needed to mark the query model property where this must be applied.

To provide the requested UX for condition definition, the UI needs to have access to the fields and their types for the 
selected object and the list of supported operators. The retrieval of this data is done by using a Value Providers 
that depends on the selected object type.

```
type QueryBuilderInputType = @QueryBuilder() {
    filter: @ResultSetFilter()
            @Discriminator(value = {key: "kind"})
                QueryFilter<@ValuesFrom(value = { name: "queryBuilderFieldsValueProvider", arguments: {objectType: "/objectType"}}) String, @ValuesFrom(value = { name: "queryBuilderOperatorsValueProvider" }) String>
}
```
Reminder: For trigger types, the @QueryBuilder() annotation must not be present.
### IMPORTANT
In a trigger use case, the watermark used is usually a field of the output object, such as a date. 
Watermarking involves complex logic that must be handled by the connector developer. So, when the filter
attribute is defined, results must not include the field used as the watermark. If not, an end user can
use that field as a filter breaking the watermarking logic ending up with wrong events. A connector developer
must handle this problem adding a filter in the value provider defined for the filter's 
query builder attribute to exclude the field used as the watermark.

```
var queryBuilderFieldsValueProviderForTrigger = queryBuilderFieldsValueProvider
    mapSuccessResult (result) -> result filter ($.value != 'since')

type QueryBuilderInputTypeTrigger = {
    filter: @ResultSetFilter()
            @Discriminator(value = {key: "kind", defaultSelection: "NONE"})
                QueryFilter<
                    @ValuesFrom(value = { name: "queryBuilderFieldsValueProviderForTrigger",
                        arguments: {objectType: "/objectType" }}) String,
                    @ValuesFrom(value = { name: "queryBuilderOperatorsValueProvider"}) String>
}
```
See how the `since` field from the selected object is not eligible in the filters fields for an end user.
This field is going to be used in the watermarking logic when the final query is built.

## Limit and Offset

Some SaaS supports defining Limit and Offset in a query. There are no extra annotations needed to support this.
```
type QueryBuilderInputType = @QueryBuilder() {
    limit: Number,
    offset: Number
}
```
## Order by

Query builders can support the capability of sorting the result set by defining an ascending or descending order to be 
applied to a given field. 

To provide the requested UX for defining the resultset ordering, the UI needs to have access 
to the fields of the selected object. The retrieval of this data is done by using a Value Provider that 
depends on the selected object type.

A FieldOrder annotation will be needed to mark the field used for defining query ordering.

```
type QueryBuilderInputType = @QueryBuilder() {
   orderBy: orderBy: @FieldOrder() Array<QueryFieldOrder<@ValuesFrom(value = { name: "orderFieldsValueProvider", arguments: {objectType: "/objectType"}}) String>>
}
```
## Dynamic output

The output type of the operation/trigger will depend on object type and the projected fields.

```
type DynamicOutputType = @MetadataProvider(value = {name: "metadataProviderForProjection", arguments: {objectType: "/objectType", fields: "/projectedFields"}}) Object
```

## Query language

The connector will have to write functions to convert the input type in the query language supported by the SaaS.
For example:
```
fun getFieldSelection(fieldsSelection: AllFieldsSelection): String = "fields(ALL)"
fun getFieldSelection<F <: String>(fieldsSelection: CustomFieldsSelection<F>): String = fieldsSelection.fields joinBy ", "

fun getValueStr(val: String) : String = "'"++ val ++ "'"
fun getValueStr(val: Number) : String = val as String
fun getValueStr(val: Null) : String = "null"
fun getValueStr(val: Array<String>) : String = "(" ++ (val map ((item) -> "'" ++ item ++ "'") joinBy ", ")  ++ ")"

fun getOperator(val: String) : String = val match {
  case "equals" -> "="
  case "isNotEqual" -> "!="
  case "lessThan" -> "<"
  case "lessThanOrEquals" -> "<="
  case "greaterThan" -> ">"
  case "greaterThanOrEquals" -> ">="
  case "isNull" -> ""
  case "in" -> "in"
  case "between" -> "between"
}

fun getCondition<F <: String, O <: String>(condition: QueryCondition<F, O>): String = do {
    var left = condition.field ++ " " ++ getOperator(condition.operator)
    var right = if (condition.operator == 'between')
                       " " ++ (condition.values as Array)[0] as String ++ " and " ++ (condition.values as Array)[1] as String
                     else if (condition.operator == 'isNull')
                        if (condition.value)
                            "= null"
                        else
                            "!= null"
                     else
                       if (condition.value?)
                         " " ++ (getValueStr(condition.value))
                       else
                         ""
    ---
    left ++ right
}

fun getFilter(filter: NoQueryFilter): String =  ""
fun getFilter<F <: String, O <: String>(filter: AndQueryFilter<F, O>): String =  if (isEmpty(filter.conditions)) "" else " WHERE " ++ (filter.conditions map getCondition($) joinBy " AND ")
fun getFilter<F <: String, O <: String>(filter: OrQueryFilter<F, O>): String =  if (isEmpty(filter.conditions)) "" else " WHERE " ++ (filter.conditions map getCondition($) joinBy " OR ")
fun getFilter<F <: String, O <: String>(filter: CustomQueryFilter<F, O>): String = if (isEmpty(filter.conditions)) "" else " WHERE " ++ filter.expression replace /[0-9]+/ with getCondition(filter.conditions[$[0]-1]!)
fun getFilter<F <: String, O <: String>(watermarkField: String,
                                        watermarkValue: String,
                                        filter: AndQueryFilter<F, O> | OrQueryFilter<F, O> | CustomQueryFilter<F, O> | NoQueryFilter) : String =
    do {
        var watermarkCondition = watermarkField ++ ">=" ++ watermarkValue
        ---
        if (isEmpty(filter.conditions))
            " WHERE " ++ watermarkCondition
        else
            " WHERE " ++ "(" ++ replaceAll(getFilter(filter)," WHERE ", "") ++ ")" ++ " AND " ++ watermarkCondition
    }

fun getOffset(offset: Number): String = " OFFSET " ++ offset as String
fun getOffset(offset: Null): String = ""

fun queryToSoql(query: QueryBuilderInputType): String = log("Query: ", "SELECT $(getFieldSelection(query.projectedFields)) FROM $(query.objectType)$(getFilter(query.filter))$(getOffset(query.offset))")
fun queryToSoqlTrigger(query: QueryBuilderInputTypeTrigger, watermarkField: String, watermarkValue: String): String = log("Query: ", "SELECT $(getFieldSelection(query.projectedFields)) FROM $(query.objectType)$(getFilter(watermarkField,watermarkValue,query.filter))$(getOffset(query.offset))")
```
### IMPORTANT
In a trigger use case (in this example), final query is built calling the `queryToSoqlTrigger` and the
watermark value and field name is needed to build the `WHERE` condition. The watermark filter must be 
always present in the `WHERE` condition as part of the filtering and must be handled by the connector developer
avoiding to expose it to an end user. Connectors that supports query builder with triggers, must support
the `AND` condition as part of the `WHERE`. If not, a connector developer can not add the watermark filter
apart from any other filter an end user can add. And this is not allowed. Watermark filter is always needed.w
